Search for AI, Automation, and Analytics

Grounding search on unstructured and structured data enhances your use of generative AI, analytics, and automation tools across the Salesforce Platform. Grounded search brings customer-specific data into applications like Einstein Copilot, Tableau, and Flow Builder, ensuring that outputs are finely tuned to your users’ intents and contexts. This alignment results in more accurate and relevant AI-generated content, deeper insights from analytics, and more efficient automation workflows for your teams and customers.

In Data Cloud, you can create a vector search index or a hybrid search index. Use vector search when your data source and search queries benefit more from semantically aware matches within a large dataset, for example, a query such as “What is Acme famous for?” Use hybrid search when your data source and search queries benefit from both a semantically aware vector search and the precision of a keyword search, such as searching for specific domain terms or product codes. For example, use hybrid search for a query such as “Does Acme motor XYZ123 use hydraulic pumps?”

Unstructured Data in Data Cloud
By bringing unstructured data into Data Cloud, you can ground your generative AI, analytics, and automation search results with business-specific data that delivers deeper insights for your users and customers.
Chunk and Vectorize Data
To add your data to Data Cloud’s search index, you must first chunk and vectorize it. Chunking break your data into meaningful chunks, and Data Cloud turns those chunks into machine-readable vector embeddings.
Vector Search
When you create vector embeddings in Data Cloud, they are added to the search index. You can perform vector search queries from apps such as Prompt Builder, Einstein Copilot, or Tableau.
Hybrid Search (Beta)
To provide relevant information to an LLM with gen AI applications and generate the correct response, requires both vector search and keyword search. Vector search understands semantic similarities and context, but lacks specific domain vocabulary. Keyword search excels at lexical similarity but not at semantic similarity. In Data Cloud, hybrid search combines the strengths of semantically aware vector search with the precision and speed of keyword search.
View Search Index Configurations
You can view details of search index configurations from the Search Index list view and the object record view.
Edit Search Index Configurations
If needed, you can edit search index configurations to add fields or file extensions for chunking . You can view but not modify other existing settings.
Delete Search Index Configurations
You can delete search index configurations from the list view and the object record view.
Billing Considerations for Unstructured Data and Search Index
When you use unstructured data and search index configurations, your data is stored and processed in Data Cloud. Use of Data Cloud features for unstructured data has billing implications. Use of Data Cloud services impacts the consumption of credits used for billing. There are four billing components for unstructured data in Data Cloud: data ingestion, data storage, data processing, and data queries. Each component has a distinct applicable usage type.
